embed: Post by Congressman Lynn Westmoreland.
label: NA
text: HOUSE FINANCIAL SERVICES COMMITTEE PASSES WESTMORELAND CFPB BILL  Today, the House Financial Services Committee passed several Consumer Financial Protection Bureau (CFPB) reformation bills, including Congressman Lynn Westmorelandâ€™s legislation, H.R. 4604, the CFPB Data Collection Security Act.   â€œThe House Financial Services Committeeâ€™s series of hearings on the CFPB prove that Americans across the nation are concerned with the amount of power the CFPB has taken for itself with no oversight or transparency,â€ stated Westmoreland. â€œThis lack of transparency, security, and congressional accountability needs to be addressed immediately. My colleagues and I have put forth a package of bills, including my bill H.R. 4604, which address major security concerns, along with combating abuse and preventing fraud, within the bureau.    â€œH.R.4604, the CFPB Data Collection Security Act is one part of addressing the bigger problem of the CFPB. This bill gives Americans the opportunity to join an opt-out list, requires the bureau to purge data, and requires a security clearance for employees dealing with sensitive information. Itâ€™s scary to think of the large amount and type of data the CFPB has access to, without giving you the option to opt-out or for those collecting that data to not have security clearances. Americans deserve peace of mind when it comes to the security of their personal information.â€   Congressman Westmoreland encourages Majority Leader Eric Cantor to quickly bring H.R. 4604 to the House floor for a vote.  To view videos of Congressman Westmoreland's opening statement at the hearing, or his reading of a list of data collection examples, please click the link below or visit his YouTube page.

embed: Post by Congressman Beto O'Rourke.
label: NA
text: Although there is already a budget in place for Fiscal Year 2015 due to last yearâ€™s passage of the Bipartisan Budget Act, this week the House considered a number of budget proposals. None of these budgets will replace the current budget for 2015, but they are useful as policy documents and lay out important priorities.   When deciding which budgets to support, I consider the following criteria: (1) whether the budget is good for El Paso, including support for veterans, Fort Bliss and the border; (2) does it put our nation on a sustainable financial path; (3) does it make the investments needed for economic growth and opportunity; (4) is it fair.  The House Majority sponsored a budget (H.Con.Res. 96) authored by Paul Ryan. Although this budget passed the House, I voted against it as it did not fulfill the four criteria above. It seeks to decrease the deficit by making deep cuts to non-defense discretionary spending and entitlements, including Medicare and Medicaid. These are the programs that provide health care, support education, pay for our CBP agents and officers along the border, and fund important transportation and infrastructure projects. The result of the Ryan budget in Texas would be over 3,500 teachers losing their jobs, 44,000 fewer students receiving Pell Grants and 12,000 fewer children enrolled in Head Start. It would also cut $48 billion in Medicaid for Texas and end the Medicare guarantee for seniors, meaning that more of our neighbors would lose health insurance or pay more for Medicare. Although it would maintain the status quo funding for the VA and the Department of Defense, it would make deep cuts to transportation and infrastructure funding, hurting our ability to modernize our nationâ€™s roads, ports and communications systems. The Ryan budget is also unfair. The proposed changes to the tax code would reduce the top tax rates from 39.6% to 25%. This would save the average millionaire approximately $200,000 each year. Unfortunately, middle class taxpayers could actually see their taxes go up by as much as $2000 as the budget would allow provisions like the child tax credit to expire. This is not a budget that is good for El Paso or fair for the country.  I did support two budget alternatives: the Representative Van Hollen substitute and the Representative Fudge substitute. Both of these budgets put the nation on a more stable fiscal footing by reducing the deficit through a mixture of changes in the tax code and targeted spending cuts that would still allow for smart investments in education and infrastructure to create jobs. These budgets would eliminate across the board sequestration cuts for the Department of Defense and replace them sensible reductions by eliminating weapons systems we do not need and extraneous overseas bases. That is good for Fort Bliss and the 11,000 civilian employees who work there. These budgets also recognize the need for common sense immigration reform, which would reduce the federal deficit by $900 billion over the next 20 years.  Finally, the Fudge substitute would adopt the Independent Budget (read more at independentbudget.org) for the VA. This is a proposal crafted by Veteran Service Organizations (VSOs) and is meant to address the current shortfalls in VA care and benefits, with a focus on dramatically increasing mental health treatment and ending the disability claims backlog. These were both budgets that would be good for El Paso.

text: Today, I took two important steps regarding the ongoing crisis on our southern border.   First, I inserted language into the Defense Appropriations Act to increase the funding available to the Army National Guard to help address the illegal immigration crisis currently taking place at our southern border. I accomplished this by transferring funding from the staffing needs of the Secretary of Defense into the funds for the Army National Guard.  Second, I cosponsored the Southwest Border Protection Act. This legislation calls for thousands of U.S. National Guard troops to be deployed at the request of any Governor of a State that shares a portion of the international border between the U.S. and Mexico. They would serve until we have gained control of the crisis at our southern border. embed: Post by Mike Conaway.
label: NA
text: Two provisions that I worked on were included in the Fiscal Year 2015 Defense Authorization Bill, which the House passed this week. One provision would require the Department of Defense to award Purple Hearts to soldiers killed in the 2009 Fort Hood shootings. I offered this amendment on behalf of Congressman John Carter (R-TX31) and Congressman Roger Williams (R-TX25), who are not on the House Armed Services Committee. As we know too well, the battlefield in the War on Terror is not limited to foreign lands. Men and women who defend America against terrorism on American soil, should be eligible to receive the Purple Heart and other medals that recognize their heroism and sacrifice. It also includes two provisions I authored that would prohibit large-scale purchases of biofuels unless they are cost competitive with traditional fuels, and require the department to submit a case analysis to Congress before constructing a biofuel refinery. These provisions are necessary at a time when our military is already facing enormous budget constraints. It is not the job of the Department of Defense to spend millions of taxpayer dollars to develop the biofuel industry when these monies could go toward service member training and readiness. While I am happy this bill passed the House, the Senate now needs to pass it and the President needs to sign it. Furthermore, we need the Presidentâ€™s leadership in rolling back the across the board cuts that are damaging our military and threatening our national security.

text: We find ourselves at the perilous point of a nearly failed state of Iraq, accompanied by the virtually unchecked movement of one of the most dangerous terrorist organizations the world has ever known, the Islamic State of Iraq and the Levant (ISIL).  I believe that ISIL presents a grave threat to our allies, our citizens, and our homeland.  However, I remain concerned that the Presidentâ€™s current strategy is insufficient to meet the challenge of defeating ISIL. I support todayâ€™s bipartisan passage of an Amendment authorizing a â€œtrain-and-equipâ€ approach because Congress added several provisions that will enhance Congressional oversight, require detailed progress reports, increase monitoring the use of equipment and demand information on how the authority fits within the Presidentâ€™s larger regional strategy.  I also believe that over the next two months, the House Armed Services Committee (HASC) and the American public would greatly benefit from the testimony of retired senior ranking military commanders who have personal experience fighting in Iraq and first-hand knowledge of strategies that have proven effective on Iraqâ€™s battlefields. I have sent a letter to HASC Chairman Buck McKeon encouraging him to hold hearings with these battlefield commanders as their perspective would provide the United States and Coalition Forces the vital insight and expertise needed to pursue the right strategy and give our warfighters everything they need to achieve victory.

embed: Post by Bill Johnson.
label: NA
text: Iâ€™m often asked by the hard working people of Eastern and Southeastern Ohio, â€œWhat have you personally done, Congressman Johnson, to address the issues facing our region, our state, and our nation?â€  Well, hereâ€™s a summary of the actions of the US House of Representatives since I came into office in January 2011.    1) I supported strong fiscal control in Washington, and forcing Washington to live with its means â€“ just like every American family has to do.  Because of these efforts, for the first time since the Korean War, total federal spending has gone down for two years in a row.  This represents the most significant spending reductions in modern history â€“ more significant than Ronald Reagan and Tip Oâ€™Neal, more significant than Bill Clinton and Newt Gingrich.  2) I supported the Budget Control Act (BCA) that was signed into law by President Obama in August, 2011.  The BCA was initiated by the Republican-led House, and it was the largest spending reduction bill of the last 25 years (and perhaps ever) - $630 billion in savings over five years all from the spending side.  Furthermore, the BCA was the largest deficit control bill since 1981 not to contain a penny in tax increases.   3) And, in 2012, I supported legislation that became law to successfully protect 99 percent of Americans from a tax increase on a permanent basis, and gave Americans increased certainty about what to expect on their taxes in the future.  This ensured that almost all of the 2003 tax policies that had kept your tax rates lower for nearly 10 years were made permanent, and it included a permanent $5 million cap on the death/estate tax and lower rates on capital gains and dividends.  Rest assured, I will continue to work hard to change the culture in Washington, DC, to eliminate the mule-headed, dig-in-your-heels at all cost partisanship that keeps our federal government in gridlock, and to ensure you have an effective, efficient federal government that puts the interests and needs of the American people above self interests and politics in Washington.

embed: Post by Rep. Paul Gosar.

text: Today the Supreme Court issued a mixed ruling on the future of the EPA and their authority to regulate American energy. The question brought to the Supreme Court was this: Can the EPA force companies to adhere to new regulations based off the EPAâ€™s interpretation of current law?  The good news first: Justice Antonin Scalia wrote in the majority opinion: â€œWe hold that EPA exceeded its statutory authority when it interpreted the Clean Air Act to requireâ€¦ permitting for stationary sources based on their greenhouse-gas emissions.â€ This part of the ruling is important in order to rein in President Obamaâ€™s attempts to circumvent Congress and unilaterally change environmental laws to fit his far-left ideology.    But here is the bad news from the Court's ruling, From Fox News: â€œThe outcome does preserve EPA's authority over facilities that already emit pollutants that the agency regulates other than greenhouse gases.â€   The EPA has already announced that this ruling clears the way for their newest scheduled regulations on current power plants which would devastate our energy providers as well as all hard working Americans across the country. This will lead to the loss of 1,000 jobs in Page, Arizona alone and approximately 224,000 jobs annually. Obama has extinguished any hope of working with Congress and his only option left is using his executive powers to force his failed agenda on the American people. This has real impacts on our pocket books and drives up gasoline prices, electricity bills and could even lead to a significant spike in water bills. This trend must be reversed. embed: Post by Justin Amash.
label: NA
text: I voted yes on #HR3189, Water Rights Protection Act. The bill prohibits the Department of the Interior and the Department of Agriculture from requiring that privately held water rights be transferred to the federal government as a condition for obtaining or renewing a federal land use permit. In 2011, the U.S. Forest Service began requiring applicants for ski area permits to transfer their privately held water rights to the United States as a permit condition. The directive was overturned in 2012 by a U.S. district court. This bill prevents any similar policies from being implemented in the future. Americans should be able to access the vast resources available on federal land, and using federal land shouldn't be contingent upon transferring the federal government your private water rights. It passed 238-174.

embed: Post by Representative Rick Crawford.
label: NA
text: On this Memorial Day, I would like to remember the life of LT Christopher Edward Mosko.  Lt. Mosko served in an EOD (Explosive Ordinance Disposal) unit in the U.S. Navy.  He was killed in action in Afghanistan a few years ago.  Please take a few minutes to read about the life of Lt. Mosko and the many awards he won defending our nation, including the Bronze Star Medal with Valor he was awarded posthumously.  Lt. Mosko is survived by his wife, Amanda, of Malvern, PA.  LT Chris Mosko was born in Worcester, Massachusetts on November 18th, 1983.  Upon graduating from Eau Claire Memorial High School in Eau Claire, WI in 2002, he attended Drexel University in Philadelphia, PA where he completed his undergraduate degree in Commerce and Engineering.  In 2007, LT Mosko graduated from Drexel and completed his time as a midshipman with the Naval Reserve Officer Training Corps at the University of Pennsylvania.  Commissioned as an Ensign in the summer of 2007, he reported to Naval Dive and Salvage Training Center in Panama City, FL to begin the arduous training to become a Navy Explosive Ordnance Disposal (EOD) Officer.  He completed Navy Dive School in October of 2007 and immediately transitioned to Naval School Explosive Ordnance Disposal onboard Eglin Air Force Base, FL where he graduated in October 2008.  Upon graduation he completed Basic Airborne Training at Fort Benning, GA and reported to Explosive Ordnance Disposal Training and Evaluation Unit ONE in San Diego, CA for advanced training in the unique mission sets of a Navy EOD Technician.  Having been awarded his EOD pin and completing his training, LT Mosko reported to Explosive Ordnance Disposal Mobile Unit THREE (EODMU THREE) in San Diego, CA.  While assigned to EODMU THREE, he supported the stand-up of Explosive Ordnance Disposal Support Unit ONE as its Assistant Operations Officer.  He then deployed onboard USS Carl Vinson (CVN-70) as Assistant Platoon Leader for PLT 3-2-2 and supported Humanitarian Operations following the earthquake in Haiti in January 2010.  LT Mosko assumed command of PLT 3-8-1 and began the challenging training, qualification, and integration with SEAL Team THREE.  He deployed his platoon to Afghanistan in support of Naval Special Warfare Squadron Three, Army 3rd Special Forces Group, and Combined Joint Special Operations Task Force â€“ Afghanistan.  LT Mosko is a qualified EOD warfare officer and Naval Parachutist.  His awards include:  Bronze Star Medal w/Valor (Posthumous)  Purple Heart (Posthumous)  Combat Action Ribbon  Navy and Marine Corps Achievement Medal  Global War on Terrorism Service Medal  Global War on Terrorism Expeditionary Medal  NATO Medal  National Defense Service Medal  Humanitarian Service Medal  Armed Forces Services Medal  Afghanistan Campaign Medal  Navy Expert Pistol Medal  Navy Expert Rifle Medal  Sea Service Deployment Ribbon

text: Proud to join U.S. Senator Barbara A. Mikulski in announcing a a $1,000,000 grant from the The United States Department of Justice Office of Juvenile Justice and Delinquency Prevention program to the Cal Ripken, Sr. Foundation. These federal grant funds will help the foundation provide mentoring opportunities for at-risk youth in #Maryland and 13 other states.  Young people are our greatest natural resources, to invest in them is to invest in a stronger future for all Americans. When it comes to serving the needs of at-risk youth, government cannot do it alone, nor can the private sector.
